#### üîé <b>Define</b>

<img src="https://images.code.org/6561d2dc9e981376f36799a1f68de5e9-image-1700514906651.14.15 PM.png" style="float:right; width:250px; border-radius:30px; margin-left:15px; margin-right: 15px;" alt="Diagram showing the four steps of the Problem Solving Process">

* #### Read the instructions carefully to make sure you understand the goals and intended outcomes of the program
* #### If there is a sample program, run it to make sure you understand what it does
* #### If there is started code, read it to understand what it does
* #### Rephrase the problem or task in your own words
* #### Identify any skills you are being asked to apply
* #### Decide which aspect of the program you want to complete first
<br>

#### üìù <b>Prepare</b>

* #### Brainstorm the different ways you could solve the entire problem using programming.
* #### Write in plain English or pseudocode your ideas for how to solve the program to do what it's supposed to do
* #### List what you already know how to do and what you don't yet
* #### Describe your ideas to a classmate
* #### Review similar programs you may have written in the past
* #### Sketch your idea on paper if needed
<br>

#### üñ•Ô∏è <b>Try</b>

* #### Pick one idea from the previous step and document why you chose that idea
* #### Implement your chosen idea and write one small piece of code at a time
* #### Test your program often
* #### Use comments to document and keep track of what your code does
* #### Go back to the previous step to look at your other ideas for solving if you get stuck
* #### Apply appropriate debugging strategies
<br>

#### ü§î <b>Reflect</b>

* #### Compare your program to the defined problem. Were you successful in solving all aspects of the problem? How do you know?
* #### Ask a classmate to try your program. Are there places where they struggle or show confusion?
* #### Ask a classmate to read your code. Is your code and documentation clear and accurate?
* #### Try to "break" your program. Did you find types of interaction or input that your program could handle better?
* #### Are there any changes or improvements you can make to this program or another one like it in the future?
</details>


